            <biogHist>
                <p>Donald MacIntyre was born around 1793, the son of fisherman Donald MacIntyre and
                    his wife Mary née Campbell.  His place of birth is not recorded.  He married Ann
                    Campbell and by the time of the 1841 census they were living in Aird, Benbecula
                    with two children: Catharine (13) and Mary (10).  He worked as a crofter and was
                    also a Roman Catholic catchist.  Ten years later, both daughters are recorded as
                    still living in the family home in 1851.  Ann MacIntyre died on 17 May 1859.  In
                    the 1861 census, Donald is recorded together with his elder daughter Catharine
                    and a grandson, Archibald (2).  </p>
                <p>Donald MacIntyre died of 'old age' on 9 August 1868 aged around 75 in Aird,
                    Benbecula with his son-in-law Angus Wilson as the recorded informant. </p>
                <p>He is mentioned in a story collected by Alexander Carmichael in which Father
                    MacGregor of South Uist is described reading Ossian to his catechist Donald
                    MacIntyre.</p>
